## 2. Add checkpoint calls (a few one-liners)

Wherever you want a capture, add ONE line. The `driver` variable is whatever
your framework already uses (often `BaseTest.driver` or `BasePage.driver`).

**The single highest-value place** — your `Hooks.java` `@After`, so every
scenario captures its final state (this alone powers failure debugging):

```java
// inside your existing @After hook, where you have access to the driver and scenario:
com.nbc.utils.CaptureAgent.capture(driver,
        scenario.isFailed() ? "OnFailure" : "AfterScenario",
        scenario.getName());
```

**Optional, higher-resolution checkpoints** — add wherever it helps, e.g.:

```java
// after login completes (in CommonSteps login method):
com.nbc.utils.CaptureAgent.capture(driver, "AfterLogin", "Login");

// after a transaction search loads its screen:
com.nbc.utils.CaptureAgent.capture(driver, "AfterTransactionSearch", "Transaction Enquiry");

// right before a submit:
com.nbc.utils.CaptureAgent.capture(driver, "BeforeSubmit", "Set Hold");
```

Start with **just the `@After` hook**. Add the others only if you want more
granular capture later.

---

## 3. Rebuild

In IntelliJ: **Build → Build Project (Ctrl+F9)**. That compiles the new class
into `target/test-classes` like any other framework file.

---

## 4. How it runs

- **Normal runs:** `capture.enabled` is absent → every `capture(...)` call
  returns instantly and does nothing. Zero effect on existing behavior.
- **Capture Mode:** the orchestrator launches java with
  `-Dcapture.enabled=true -Dcapture.run=<id> -Dcapture.txn=<n>
  -Dcapture.endpoint=http://127.0.0.1:8000/capture/ingest`, and every
  checkpoint pushes a capture to the Python side, viewable at `/capture/list`
  and automatically fed into AI locator generation.

The POST is async and failure-swallowed by design: if the orchestrator is down
or slow, your test run is completely unaffected.

---

## Security note

The Python side sanitizes captured HTML (redacts `value="..."` on inputs and
passwords) before writing anything to disk, so account numbers and passwords
typed into the page are not persisted. Screenshots are stored as-is because
they are needed for later vision analysis — if your screens display full
account numbers, treat `data/runtime_capture/` as sensitive and keep it off any
shared drive, same as you already do for `config.py`.
